                     <interp inst="def1-1978-18470816" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1978-18470816" type="age" value="17"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1978-18470816" type="surname" value="JENKINS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1978-18470816" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM JENKINS</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18470816-1978-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18470816-1978-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="royalOffences"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18470816-1978-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="coiningOffences"></interp> for unlawfully uttering counter<lb></lb>feit coin.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. BODKIN</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">DAWSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470816-name-1326" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1326" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1326" type="surname" value="DROUET"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1326" type="given" value="HANNAH"></interp>HANNAH DROUET.</persName>
                  </hi> My husband is a licensed victualler, and lives in Hon-lane, Woolwich—on the 3rd of June, between nine and ten o'clock at night, the prisoner came and asked for a small glass of spruce—it came to 1<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—he</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184708160233"></xptr>
               <p>gave me a shilling—I gave him the change—he went away—I put the shilling into the till—I am quite sure there was no other shilling there—I looked particularly at it, and said I did not think it was good—the prisoner said yes, it was a good one—I sounded it—Gladwin the policeman came in and asked me to allow him to look at the shilling—I gave it him—when I took it out of the, I still found it was the only shilling there—I marked it and gave it the officer—this is it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470816-name-1327" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1327" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1327" type="surname" value="GLADWIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1327" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM GLADWIN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman R</hi> 122.) I saw the prisoner in Mrs. Drouet's house—she gave me this shilling.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470816-name-1328" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1328" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1328" type="surname" value="WATSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1328" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES WATSON.</persName>
                  </hi> I keep the While Horse, at Charlton—on the 4th of June, about nine o'clock in the evening, the prisoner came to my house and asked for a pennyworth of spruce—I served him—he tendered me a piece of money purporting to be a shilling—I gave him a 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. and 5<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in coppers, in change—he left the house—my ostler stood behind me and said, "I have a suspicion that this is a passer of bad money, he has been here before"—I never put the shilling out of my hand—I sent my son and the ostler after the prisoner for a mile, and I followed leisurely after them as far as a toll-gate—in a quarter of an hour I saw the prisoner again—he had avoided the main road—I took him coming through the gate—I said, "Young man, you have been to my house and passed a bad shilling for a pennyworth of spruce"—he denied being at my house at all, and did not know me—I took him back to my house—on the road he asked me to let him look at the shilling—I said, "No, I have got the shilling, you must give a better account of yourself"—he asked me to give it him back, and said he would give me a good one.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470816-name-1329" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1329" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1329" type="surname" value="WADLOW"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1329" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY WADLOW</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman R</hi> 267.) On the 4th of June I apprehended the prisoner at Mr. Watson's—I produce this bad shilling, which I received from Mr. Watson—I found on the prisoner a shilling, a sixpence, and five<lb></lb>pence in halfpence, all good—he said he had not been in the town more than two hours.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You questioned him about having been at Mr. Watson's, and he said afterwards he had been there? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—this case has been standing over for two months.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470816-name-1330" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1330" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1330" type="surname" value="POWELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1330" type="given" value="CALEB EDWARD"></interp>CALEB EDWARD POWELL.</persName>
                  </hi> I am inspector of coin to the Royal Mint. These shillings are both counterfeit, and have been cast in one mould.</p>
